1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Evesham, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pembridge, , Herefordshire, England":"Pembridge, Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1310–":"1310–Deceased","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","about 1335":"about 1335","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Evesham, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Pembridge, , Herefordshire, England":"Pembridge, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plowfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Blofield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Blofield","meanings":["English: locative name from Blofield (Norfolk)."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Plowfield was born in 1310, in Pembridge, Herefordshire, England. He married Mrs. Hugh Plowfield in 1335. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He was buried in Pembridge, Herefordshire, England."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Evesham, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pembridge, , Herefordshire, England":"Pembridge, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1310–":